  "25-4": (
    caption: [Defining DNA strands at the replication fork. A new DNA strand (light red) is always synthesized in the 59S39 direction. The tem- plate is read in the opposite direction, 39S59. The leading strand is con- tinuously synthesized in the direction taken by the replication fork. The other strand, the lagging strand, is synthesized discontinuously in short pieces (Okazaki fragments) in a direction opposite to that in which the replication fork moves. The Okazaki fragments are spliced together by DNA ligase. In bacteria, Okazaki fragments are (cid:2)1,000 to 2,000 nucleo- tides long. In eukaryotic cells, they are 150 to 200 nucleotides long.],
